Date: 11/10/1769
Source: Cook's Journals
Author:
Vol / Page: I: 572
Edition:
Quote: The third sort of Ahou [cloak] seemed to be made of the Cloth Plant coarsely beat out or of a kind of narrow Sedge or course [sic] grass- ... the ends of the stuff of about a foot long were left out so as to form a thick covering layer over layer, and very much resembled what Seamen call thrum-Matts.
Notes: W.B. Monkhouse in 1955

Date: 24/4/1773
Source: Resolution Journal of J.R. Forster, The
Author: FORSTER
Vol / Page: 2 : 262
Edition:
Quote: ... the Capt went up to them & nosed them, & then they gave him a  new Ahoo, for which present the Capt returned a Hatchet ...
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1773
Source: Cook's Journals
Author:
Vol / Page: 2 : 740
Edition:
Quote: Their Cloathing (both Men [and] Women) is a kind of matt or cloth made of silk grass or fine flax, curiously wove and tied about the shoulder that reaches to their knees ... [they] call it an Ahow, [fn ahu] and over it they have one of a coarser sort made of Grass well thrumbed with the same to keep out the wet which they call a Bugy Bugy. [fn] pakepake often made of undressed flax.
Notes: Furneaux's Narrative in 1961

Date: 4/6/1773
Source: Historical Records
Author: McNAB
Vol / Page: 2 : 208
Edition:
Quote: He has [check ?had] a fine furred Ahoo or mantle covered with furr [sic], before him sat a lusty middle aged man with a black Ahoo with a few bits of white fur varigated here & there a bit. <i>Ibid.</i> 2: 212 We bought great quantities of fine Flax of them, & great numbers of Ahooes or mantles made of the flax exceeding neat.
Notes: Bayly's Journal in 1908 McNab

Date: 0/0/1961
